<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Erasable Read-Only Memory" class="currentChild" href="Erasable_Read-Only_Memory">Erasable Read-Only Memory</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
A type of <a title="read-only memory" class="nonexistent" href="http://printwiki.org/read-only_memory">read-only memory</a> chip which can be erased and programmed with new data. EROM chips are used for <a title="flash memory" class="nonexistent" href="http://printwiki.org/flash_memory">flash memory</a>. See <a title="Flash Memory" class="nonexistent" href="http://printwiki.org/Flash_Memory">Flash Memory</a>. EROM is also called <a title="EPROM" class="nonexistent" href="http://printwiki.org/EPROM">EPROM</a> (for <a title="erasable programmable read-only meory" class="nonexistent" href="http://printwiki.org/erasable_programmable_read-only_meory">erasable programmable read-only meory</a>). EROM memory can be erased using ultraviolet light. EROM that is erased using an electrical current is known as <a title="EEPROM" href="EEPROM">EEPROM</a>. 
</p>
